player.seasonOutlook: Williams signed with the Bears after opting out in 2020. The 29-year-old was no more than a change-of-pace back during his first four NFL seasons (all with Miami), but made a big leap in Kansas City. Consider: Williams played at least 49% of the snaps in 16 games with the Chiefs. He handled 13.3 carries and 5.3 targets per game during those weeks, which has allowed him 278 touches for 1534 yards and 21 TDs. His numbers add up to 340.4 fantasy points, which would have ranked second to only Alvin Kamara last season. Unfortunately, Williams is ticketed for clear backup duties in Chicago, with David Montgomery, Tarik Cohen and sixth-round rookie Khalil Herbert in the mix. Williams isn't worth a draft pick.

Carolina drafted Hubbard in the fourth round of April's draft. Hubbard has been busy the past three seasons at Oklahoma State, racking up 585 carries and 67 targets on 1,514 snaps. He stands 6-foot-1, 207 pounds and showed serviceable ability as both as rusher and receiver while also chipping in as a kick returner, though his elusiveness doesn't stack up with this year's top RB prospects. Hubbard has struggled with fumbles (11 in his career) and his efficiency plummeted in seven 2020 games after a terrific breakout campaign in 2019 that saw him produce 2,292 yards and 21 touchdowns in 13 games. Hubbard is the favorite to slide in as a Mike Davis replacement behind Christian McCaffrey. The rookie is an interesting deep-league insurance option.

Williams is a 26-year-old former UDFA with 128 career regular season touches, but he's on the fantasy radar as the probable No. 2 back on the high-scoring Chiefs' depth chart (his top competition is Jerick McKinnon). Williams made some noise last season when he clearly outplayed Le'Veon Bell during three games Clyde Edwards-Helaire was sidelined. Williams more than doubled Bell in snaps, while racking up 210 yards on 38 touches, compared to 100 yards on 23 touches for Bell. The departure of Bell and Damien Williams sets up Darrel Williams as an intriguing insurance option behind the talented, but still unproven Edwards-Helaire. Williams will be well worth a bench spot in most formats.

Jackson is entering his fourth year in the NFL having yet to play more than 16% of the Chargers' offensive snaps in a single season. The 2018 seventh-round pick has flashed at times (4.9 YPC and 2.0 YAC on 138 career carries) and has some decent pass-catching ability (6.1 YPT on 54 career targets), but he's yet to carve out a consistent role in the pros. The 26-year old-will, once again, battle for primary early-down complimentary duties behind Austin Ekeler in 2021, but he's unlikely to find his way to weekly flex consideration. Even if Ekeler misses time, Jackson will work in a committee and could struggle for RB2 production. Jackson is no more than a late-round flier.

Ahmed went undrafted last year, but the former Washington Husky leapt onto the fantasy radar when Myles Gaskin went down with an injury last season. In the three games in which he played at least 60% of the snaps, Ahmed totaled 291 yards and two TDs on 63 touches. He was fantasy's No. 7 RB those weeks. Ahmed was reduced to a complementary role once Gaskin returned and will compete with newcomer Malcolm Brown for No. 2 duties in 2021. The 22-year-old is no more than an insurance option and doesn't need to be drafted.

Mack somewhat surprisingly re-signed with the Colts during the offseason after a lost 2020 campaign in which he went down with a torn ACL in Week 1. The 2017 fourth-round pick ranked top-10 in carries, rushing yards and rushing TDs in 2019, but he's now well behind second-year Jonathan Taylor on a depth chart that also includes passing-game specialist Nyheim Hines. Even if Taylor were to miss time, consider that despite reaching 900 rushing yards and eight TDs in each of this past two seasons, Mack has never posted a top-20 fantasy campaign. Injuries (he's missed at least two games in each of his four NFL seasons) and a minimal workload as a receiver (81 career targets) have proven problematic. The 25-year-old does not need to be drafted.

Scott has spent the past two seasons as a reserve behind Miles Sanders and will compete with rookie Kenneth Gainwell for the same role in 2021. The 2018 sixth-round pick barely saw the field with Sanders played, but was handed the keys to the backfield all four weeks Sanders was sidelined in 2020. Scott delivered 304 yards and one TD on 60 touches those weeks, which allowed him the 19th-most fantasy points. The 26-year-old is a solid scat back, but hasn't been a particularly inspiring RB2 even when called on to start. With Gainwell and Jordan Howard in the mix, Scott's value as an insurance option isn't as appealing as it once was.

Gallman signed with the 49ers after spending his first four NFL seasons with the Giants. The 2017 fourth-round pick has yet to play a full 16-game season, but he is coming off a career year. Filling in for an injured Saquon Barkley, Gallman posted a 147-682-6 rushing line and averaged what was easily a career-best 4.6 YPC (2.0 YAC) despite facing 7.3 box defenders per attempt (third highest). The 26-year-old has struggled as a pass catcher (career 4.2 yards per target), but 49ers’ backs aren’t asked to do much of that anyway. With Jeff Wilson Jr. injured, Gallman will compete with Raheem Mostert and rookie Trey Sermon for work in an always productive San Francisco backfield. He’s a fine bench hold.

Firsker has operated as a situational player during his first three seasons in the league, but the 2018 UDFA is positioned for a larger role for the Titans in 2021 following the departure of Jonnu Smith. After maxing out at 24 targets during his first two seasons, Firkser hit career-best marks in targets (52), receptions (39) and yardage (387) in 2020. He's scored exactly one TD in each of his three seasons, though the one in 2020 came during an impressive 8-113-1 showing with Smith out in Week 6. Tennessee ranks sixth in fantasy points scored by TEs over the past two seasons, so perhaps Firkser can take his game up in notch in 2021. The 26-year-old is a sleeper, but only worth drafting in very deep leagues.

Jones returns for a third season as the Giants' starter in what is undoubtedly a make-or-break campaign. The 2019 sixth-overall pick was under center for 14 games last season and the Giants' offense finished dead last in TDs. Jones accounted for 12 scores, while throwing 10 INTs and leading the NFL in fumbles (with 11) for the second straight season. Despite the struggles (which include a career 6.6 YPA), there's reason for optimism. Jones is entering his third season at only 24 years old, he adds value with his legs (he's ranked seventh at QB in rushing yards both seasons) and his supporting cast will be significantly better with Kenny Golladay, Kadarius Toney and Kyle Rudolph joining Evan Engram, Sterling Shepard, Darius Slayton and a healthy Saquon Barkley. Jones is a back-end QB2, but there's post-hype breakout potential.

Bateman was selected by Baltimore with the 27th overall pick of April's draft. He has decent size at 6-foot-1, 210 pounds and projects as a perimeter/X receiver in the pros. The Minnesota product is a physical receiver with good route running, speed (reportedly ran a 4.39 40) and post-catch ability. A high-volume target and vertical threat, Bateman handled a prospect-high 43% of his team's air yards in 2020 (albeit in only five games) and a 32% target share over the past three seasons. Volume figures to elude him in Baltimore, however, as the Lamar Jackson-led offense leans heavily on the run and he'll also need to fend off Marquise Brown, Mark Andrews and perhaps Sammy Watkins for targets. This is not an ideal short-term landing spot, so Bateman is no more than a late-round flier in season-long leagues.

Smith's first three seasons in New Orleans have been rather uninspiring, as the 2018 third-round pick has yet to clear 51 targets in a season. Shaky durability (he's missed seven games over the past two seasons) and a role as a blocker and short-area target (9.9 aDOT) have left Smith without a top-70 fantasy campaign. Smith's low aDOT is surprising considering his size, speed and profile as a vertical weapon. Perhaps that part of his game will be unlocked with conservative Drew Brees out and aggressive Jameis Winston or Taysom Hill in at quarterback. Note that Smith has seen six-plus targets in six career games and two those were during Hill's four 2020 starts. Michael Thomas is the only WR above Smith on New Orleans' depth chart, so there's post-hype appeal. Consider Smith with a late-round flier.

Brown signed with the Raiders after two seasons in Buffalo. Back in 2019, the 2014 third-round pick posted a 72-1,060-6 receiving line and was WR15 in fantasy prior to resting in Week 17. He struggled with injuries last season, however, and was WR35 during nine active weeks (33-458-3). Durability continues to be an issue for Brown, as he has managed two 16-game seasons in seven years and has missed 14 games over the past four seasons. The 31-year-old has a path to a No. 1 WR gig in Las Vegas, with unproven Henry Ruggs III his top competition. Consistency may be an issue in the Raiders' run-first scheme, but Brown has never been below the 70th percentile in aDOT and is a good bet to hit for occasional big plays. Consider Brown for your bench, as WR3 production is attainable.

Toney was selected by the Giants with the 20th overall pick of April's draft. The Florida product is a 5-foot-11, 193-pound slot receiver oft utilized in a gadget role with the Gators. His 6.7 aDOT since 2018 is one of the lowest in this year's class, and his overall volume was limited by suspension and multiple injuries. He did, however, catch a class-high 90% of his catchable targets and posted a strong 8.5 RAC during that span. Toney's quickness and RAC jump off the page, and he has the physical tools, explosiveness and hands to emerge into a star in the pros. He does have a bit of a crowded path to rookie-season targets, however, with Kenny Golladay, Sterling Shepard, Darius Slayton in the mix at WR, and Evan Engram and Saquon Barkley also ticketed for work. Toney is a logical late-round flier.

Collins was selected by Houston in the third round of April's draft. The Michigan product is one of the biggest receivers in this year's class at 6-foot-4, 215 pounds. He has good speed and hands to go with his huge frame, but separation, route running and RAC are concern areas. Prior to opting out in 2020, Collins was targeted often downfield but also lived on the shallow route, which he ran a class-high 25% of the time during 2018-19. Brandin Cooks is the top WR in Houston, but with Anthony Miller in the slot, the team's No. 2 perimeter gig is wide open. If Collins shows well and beats out Chris Conley, he could sneak onto the fantasy radar. He's a name to monitor in season-long leagues.

Watkins signed with the Ravens after three underwhelming seasons (at least from a fantasy perspective) with the Chiefs. Injuries were the primary culprit, as Watkins missed 14 regular-season games, including at least two all three years, but he also didn't do much when active. In 34 regular-season games, Watkins reached 15 fantasy points five times -- and those five games accounted for 40% of his point total of 341 during the three seasons. Watkins is now 28 years old and hasn't posted a top-40 fantasy season since 2015 (he's never finished a season better than 20th). He was already a poor fantasy option in pass-heavy Kansas City, so despite a possible starting gig, a move to run-heavy Baltimore doesn't help his prospects. Watkins is worth a look only in very deep non-PPR leagues.

Cousins is back as Minnesota's starter after what was arguably his best NFL season. Cousins finished top-10 in completion percentage for the sixth consecutive season, ranked third in the NFL in YPA (8.3) and tossed a career-high 35 TDs. Believe it or not, the Vikings' offense tied for fifth in the NFL with 55 TDs in 2020. That included at least three scores in 13 of 16 games. Cousins adds the bare minimum with his legs and hasn't posted a top-10 fantasy campaign since 2017, so even with Justin Jefferson, Adam Thielen and Dalvin Cook at his disposal, the 33-year-old is best viewed as a mid-range QB2 with limited upside in Minnesota's run-heavy scheme.

"Fitzmagic" signed with Washington - his ninth NFL team - during the offseason. The 38-year-old hasn't played a 16-game season since 2015, but has been productive when called upon during the span. Counting only weeks in which he played a majority of the snaps, he was QB3 in five games in 2018, QB3 in 12 games in 2019 and QB6 in seven games last season. Fitzpatrick's risky style of play has led to a lot of INTs (68 in 68 games since 2015), but also plenty of big plays, TDs (110) and, of course, fantasy points. Fitzpatrick's aggressive nature and ability to add a few points with his legs is enough to make him a weekly streaming option, and Washington's failure to draft a QB means he may hang on to the job for the entire season. Consider him a QB2 on draft day.

Miami's D/ST was the biggest riser of 2020, leaping to eighth after a dreadful last-place finish in 2019. The Dolphins paced the NFL with 18 INTs and 28 forced turnovers, while ranking fifth in points allowed and 10th in sacks. No defense has repeated as the leader in forced turnovers in more than a decade (several dropped off considerably), but Miami will return most of its defensive core, including star CB duo Xavien Howard and Byron Jones, as well as recent first-round picks Christian Wilkins and Noah Igbinoghene. Kyle Van Noy was a notable loss, but that may be offset be first-round pick Jaelan Phillips and impact off-ball LB Benardrick McKinney. Jakeem Grant also returns, having scored at least one return TD four of the past five seasons. Expect a solid season from Miami's D/ST.

The Saints' D/ST has finished as a top-10 unit three of the past four seasons, including sixth in 2020. The Saints led the NFL with 18 INTs last season and also ranked no lower than eighth in sacks, yards allowed points allowed and forced turnovers. Despite the recent success, a step back could be in the cards in 2021. Janoris Jenkins, Trey Hendrickson, Alex Anzalone and Sheldon Rankins are among the offseason departures for a cash-strapped New Orleans team that will be forced to replace them with rookies. Marcus Williams, David Onyemata, Marshon Lattimore, Demario Davis, Cameron Jordan and Malcolm Jenkins are among the unit's returning stars, though the latter three are all at least 32 years old. Consider New Orleans' D/ST a weekly streaming option.

Seattle selected Eskridge with the 56th overall pick of April's draft. The Western Michigan product is undersized (5-foot-9, 188 pounds), but the former track star's elite speed and strong post-catch production led to a 21.8 YPR (first in this year's WR class), as well as 3.6 YPRR and 9.6 RAC marks (both second) over the past three seasons at Western Michigan. Despite the strong efficiency, Eskridge ran a limited route tree and his route running, ball skills, physicality, production in contested situations, size and age (24) are all concern areas. The No. 3 WR gig in Seattle is wide open behind stars D.K. Metcalf and Tyler Lockett, but that position hasn't been particularly productive in fantasy in recent years. Likely to work as a situational deep threat and returner, Eskridge is worth no more than a late-round pick.

Kirk is entering his fourth year with Arizona having fallen short of expectations thus far in his young career. The 2018 second-round pick has yet to play more than 14 games in a season and has ranked near the basement in YPRR each of the past two seasons. He peaked with a 68-709-3 receiving line and was WR38 in fantasy back in 2019, but that required a very generous 24% target share (16th highest). Kirk's usage dipped with DeAndre Hopkins in the fold in 2020 (8.1 to 5.5 targets per game) and may again in 2021 with A.J. Green and rookie Rondale Moore added to the mix. Kirk is only 24 years old, but even in a good Arizona offense, he's a longshot for consistent flex production. At best, he's worth a late draft pick.

Lazard opened 2020 as Green Bay's No. 2 WR opposite Davante Adams and delivered a 4-63-1 receiving line in Week 1 before laying down a 6-146-1 line two weeks later with Adams sidelined. Lazard then missed seven weeks with an injury before totaling 355 yards and two TDs in his final nine games (including two playoff games). The 25-year-old produces the occasional big game and benefits from an Aaron Rodgers-led offense, but the return of Randall Cobb will cut his targets and his painfully inconsistent usage and production make him nearly impossible to trust in weekly lineups. The 25-year-old is fine for a bench spot, but his best value is in DFS tournaments.

Slayton was a terrific find by the Giants in the fifth round of the 2019 draft. The vertical weapon came out of the gate with a 48-740-8 receiving line in 14 games as a Day 3 rookie (WR37 in fantasy) before taking a step back (50-751-3 in 16 games) in 2020. Slayton ranked in the 80th percentile in aDOT in both seasons, but an ugly 52% catch rate and disappointing TD total in New York's struggling offense crushed his fantasy output in 2020 (three top-30 weeks). The 24-year-old is set to play a reduced role in 2021 with Kenny Golladay and first-round pick Kadarius Toney added to an offense that also includes Sterling Shepard, Evan Engram and a healthy Saquon Barkley. Slayton is worth a late flier only in deep non-PPR leagues.

Jefferson was active for all 18 of the Rams' games and was on the field for 24% of the team's offensive snaps as a rookie last season. The second-round pick wasn't close to a fantasy factor during the regular season (2.9 PPG) but came through with a decent showing in place of Cooper Kupp in the divisional round against Green Bay (6-46-1 receiving line on seven targets). Jefferson is "old" for a second-year player (25), but will play a larger role in 2021 if he can fend off 34-year-old DeSean Jackson and rookie Tutu Atwell for No. 3 duties behind Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp. Considering his pedigree, and with Matthew Stafford under center and Sean McVay running the ship, Jefferson is the type of player you want to be targeting in the late rounds of deep leagues.

Hamler is entering his second NFL season after appearing in 13 games as a rookie. The Penn State product was targeted 10 times in back-to-back games (Weeks 9-10) but totaled 37 targets in his other 11 outings. The second-round pick's efficiency was very poor, as he ranked near the basement in catch rate (53%), YPT (6.7), YPRR (1.2) and drop rate (8.8%), while managing two top-40 fantasy weeks. Hamler is a small (5-foot-9, 178 pounds) and fast slot WR who has a lot of competition for targets with Courtland Sutton, Jerry Jeudy, Tim Patrick and Noah Fant in the mix in a run-first Denver offense lacking a proven QB. Hamler is a fine late-round flier considering his talent, but consistent fantasy output seems unlikely.

Jackson signed with the Rams after appearing in a grand total of eight games during the past two seasons in Philadelphia. In fact, Jackson last appeared in a full 16-game regular season in 2013 and is averaging 10.4 games per season since that point. Jackson occasionally looks like his old self (he had an 8-154-2 showing in 2019 Week 1 and caught an 81-yard TD in Week 16 last season), but the lack of availability has become a major issue. In Los Angeles, he's likely to work as a situational deep threat while rotating with Van Jefferson and rookie Tutu Atwell behind Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp. Jackson's propensity for big plays makes him a tempting fantasy best-ball flier, but the 34-year-old's durability concerns are as high as anyone in the NFL.

Robinson has been active for all 90 of the Chiefs' regular-season games since he was drafted in 2016. That's extremely rare durability and availability, though it hasn't translated into much fantasy value. Robinson hit career-high marks in targets (58), receptions (45) and receiving yards (466) last season, but none of those ranked better than 64th among WRs, and he has yet to finish a season better than 69th in fantasy points. Robinson runs a lot of routes but isn't overly efficient, nor is he targeted much, as shown by his career 0.96 YPRR (second worst among WRs with 160-plus targets since 2016). The 26-year-old will continue to soak up snaps in Kansas City but is a longshot for consistent flex appeal and shouldn't be drafted.

A 2020 fourth-round pick, Kelley exploded out of the gate with 37 touches (13th-most) during his first two NFL games. His efficiency was not particularly good, however, and his playing time decreased from there. That includes a seven-game stretch (Weeks 4-11) in which Austin Ekeler was out with an injury. Kelley ended the season 43rd among RBs with 134 touches, but failed to post a single weekly fantasy finish better than 25th. He posted a 3.2 YPC (16th-worst among 551 RBs with a 100-plus carry season since 2009) and 1.2 YAC (20th-worst), but did catch all but one of his 24 targets. The 23-year-old entered the pros with an underwhelming elusiveness profile and that translated to the pros. He'll compete with Justin Jackson for work behind Ekeler again this season, but has little upside.

Gainwell was selected by Eagles in the fifth round of April's draft. The Memphis product is 5-foot-11, 201 pounds and an undersized scat back with average speed who figures to make his name as a pass catcher and perhaps in the slot WR in the pros. Gainwell's receiving prowess is apparent, as he averaged a massive 9.7 YPT during his final two FBS seasons. Gainwell opted out of the 2020 season, so we haven't seen him in a while, and, though he did handle a big workload in 2019, his size and skillset is unlikely to allow him much goal line work or a three-down role in the pros. He'll open his career battling Boston Scott for change-of-pace/passing-down role behind feature back Miles Sanders. Draft the rookie in only very deep PPR leagues.

Winston re-signed with the Saints during the offseason and, though he'll need to fend of Taysom Hill, the expectation is that he will replace Drew Brees as the team's starter. Winston was limited to 11 pass attempts in his first season with New Orleans, but you may recall his thrilling 2019 season in Tampa Bay in which he threw 33 TDs while pacing the NFL in passing yards (5,109) and INTs (30). The New Orleans offense will look much different with Winston, as where Brees has been extremely conservative and accurate, Winston is much more aggressive: he has never finished a season lower than third in average depth of throw. Winston has Sean Payton calling the shots and Michael Thomas and Alvin Kamara at his disposal, so while not a safe pick, the 27-year-old has the upside to warrant a late-round flier.

Carr returns for his eighth season as the Raiders' starter. He has yet to finish an NFL season lower than 14th in pass attempts, but he's yet to post a top-10 fantasy campaign. He finished 13th last season despite pushing the ball down field more often (career-high 8.2 average depth of throw), which led to a career-best 7.94 YPA. Carr simply didn't handle enough volume (outside the top-10 in attempts, yards and pass TDs), doesn't add much with his legs (his 39-140-3 rushing line in 2020 was easily a career best) and has an underwhelming supporting cast. The 30-year-old has settled in as a mid-to-back-end QB2 with limited upside.

Wilson was selected by the Jets with the second overall pick of April's draft. Though undersized (6-foot-2, 214 pounds), the BYU product checks a lot of boxes, sporting terrific arm strength and accuracy, as well as mobility. His collegiate efficiency was elite, as his completion rate (74%) and INT rate (0.9%) were both near the top of the class despite a gunslinger mentality that led to him pushing the ball down field at one of the highest rates (10.2 average depth of throw). Wilson scored 43 TDs (10 rushing) and thew three INTs in 2020. Wilson will be New York's Week 1 starter but is a longshot for immediate fantasy contributions in a rebuilding Jets' offense that finished last in TDs last season. Consider him with a late pick in deeper leagues.

Cook is entering his 13th NFL season and is now with the Chargers after spending the past two seasons in New Orleans. Cook posted a pair of top-seven fantasy campaigns in 2018-19 before seeing a dip in playing time and efficiency that dropped him to 18th last season. The 34-year-old appeared to be showing his age when his snaps were reduced around midseason, but he rebounded down the stretch, including a 7-125-1 receiving line on nine targets during a pair of playoff games. Cook is Los Angeles' de facto Hunter Henry replacement, though 23-year-old Donald Parham and perhaps third-round rookie Tre' McKitty will factor in as well. Cook figures to play roughly half the snaps in a productive Justin Herbert-led offense, which positions him as a low-ceiling TE2.

Trautman is entering his second NFL season in position for a much larger role following the offseason departures of Jared Cook and Josh Hill. Trautman - a 2020 third-round pick - played 37% of snaps as a rookie, but was limited to a 15-171-1 receiving line on 16 targets. He's big (6-foot-5, 255 pounds) and a capable blocker with good hands and athleticism (his 6.78 three cone was best at the position at the 2020 combine), which suggests a potential every-down role with receiving contributions is on the table. The Dayton product is far from a sure thing, especially with the Saints' uncertain QB situation, but he's a logical breakout candidate and thus a fine late-round sleeper.

Jarwin entered the 2020 season positioned for a breakout as Dallas' starting TE. Instead, he tore his ACL in Week 1 and replacement Dalton Schultz stepped in and delivered a TE11 fantasy campaign. Jarwin now enters his fifth NFL season having yet to post a top-25 fantasy campaign, though the 2017 UDFA signing did flash some upside with a 7-119-3 receiving line in Week 17 of the 2018 season. He's been efficient on 78 career targets, with a healthy 76% catch rate and 8.8 YPT. Jarwin is no longer assured a full-time role after Schultz's emergence and, even if he lands the No. 1 gig, he'll be no higher than fourth (perhaps fifth) in line for targets. However, this is a potentially-elite offense, so Schultz is worthy of late-round consideration.

Everett signed with Seattle after four seasons with the division-rival Rams. The 2017 second-round pick failed to live up to his pedigree in Los Angeles, never clearing 57% of the snaps or a 12% target share during a single season. He's finished just outside the top-20 in fantasy points each of the past three seasons. His 417 yards in 2020 were a career-high, but his six drops were second-most at the position and he scored one TD (he's yet to clear three in a season). Perhaps Everett will be unlocked in Seattle, but the 27-year-old failed to emerge in a good Rams' offense and will need to fend off Will Dissly for a starting gig. Everett is nothing more than a deep sleeper.
